ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

*****
[2]
Date: Mon 20 Oct 2008
Source: NBC 10 Philadelphia PA [edited]
<http://www.nbc10.com/health/17763751/detail.html>


The Philadelphia Department of Public Health is warning people of a
potential danger associated with keeping baby turtles as pets.

Health department officials report the number of cases of salmonella
poisoning linked to turtles has tripled in recent months, and the
majority of those getting sick are young children, including tiny infants.

To reduce one's risk of getting sick, the health department
recommends the following tips:

- Do not buy turtles with shells less than 4 inches long.
- Remove all reptiles from the house before bringing a new baby home.
- Do not clean the turtle's tank in the kitchen sink.
- Always wash hands after handling a turtle.
- Do not let turtles roam freely through the house.
- The health department said bleach is effective at disinfecting
areas where turtles have been.
- Salmonellosis is a bacterial illness; the disease is especially
dangerous to anyone with a compromised immune system.
- The health department wants people to dispose of turtles humanely.
The reptiles can be turned in to the Philadelphia Animal Care and
Control Association.
- Releasing pet turtles into the wild violates Pennsylvania Game
Commission regulations.

